
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `groups` baraye neshan dadaneh grooh-haayi ke yek karbar ozv-e aan ast estefadeh mishavad. Agar esm-e karbar dadeh nashavad, grooh-haaye karbar-e fa'aal neshan dadeh mishavand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `groups [USERNAME]` --> 👤 Grooh-haaye karbar-e moshakhas ra neshan midahad. Agar esm-e karbar dadeh nashavad, grooh-haaye karbar-e fa'aal neshan dadeh mishavad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ groups

    🔹 Neshan dadaneh grooh-haaye karbar-e fa'aal.

    $ groups ali

    🔹 Neshan dadaneh grooh-haaye karbari baa name "ali".

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ groups username
    username : group1 group2 group3

    🔹  Dar in mesal, karbar "username" ozv-e grooh-haaye "group1", "group2", va "group3" ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `groups` command is used to display the groups a user belongs to. If no username is provided, it shows the groups for the current user.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `groups [USERNAME]` --> 👤 Shows the groups for a specified user. If no username is provided, shows the groups for the current user.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ groups

    🔹 Shows the groups of the current user.

    $ groups alice

    🔹 Shows the groups of the user named "alice".

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ groups user1
    user1 : groupA groupB groupC

    🔹 In this example, the user "user1" belongs to the groups "groupA", "groupB", and "groupC".
